Boy am I glad the Amiga file system is redundant.  Let me relate a
story . . .

Saturday morning I was doing some complicated macro hacking in
micrognuemacs, when, unbeknownst to me, I accidentally overwrote
a very important file on one of my floppies.  Let me say that this
file was extremely important, that I had been building it over
the past two years, and no monetary value could be placed on it.

That afternoon I went back to add something to the file, when I
noticed the catastrophe.  Shit, said I.  And then some other
choice swear words.  Then I went to a movie to think about my
life without that file.

But the hacker in me would not give up.  So, I write protected and
made several copies of the diskette, and then tried to recover
the file with some of the many disk editor programs on the Fish
disks.  I couldn't get the file back with any of them.  Disksalv
failed because the disk was hunky-dory, and the file was so large
that I couldn't patch the pieces back together with a disk editor.

So, I wrote a small program which simply dumped to an ASCII file
the contents of every block on that disk that didn't have the
contents of a freshly formatted disk.  I then wrote another program
which pieced as many fragments of each file together as it could,
and wrote them all out to disk.  These programs took about an hour
to write.

Well, I ran them, and after a little debugging, I had about eight
`files' in my RAM disk.  I examined them one by one, and wallah
:-) one of them was my original file, completely intact.  This was
only possible because of all the redundancy; pointers to the next
block in each block, pointers back to the original file block, and
sequence numbers.

So my life goes on, all hunky-dory, and I continue to work.  And
once again I learn the importance of backups, by not having one.

